                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1558">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 312.51/68.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Department of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Spanish Embassy</gloss>.</hi>
                    <note n="147" xml:id="d1558fn147">Mutatis mutandis to French and Italian
                        Embassies.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-08-05">
                            <hi rend="italic">August 5, 1914</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p rend="center">
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">memorandum</hi>.</p>
                <p>The American Vice Consul at Saltillo recently telegraphed the Department from
                    Tampico in connection with the treatment of persons and property belonging to
                    religious orders and suggested that the Government of Spain, as a measure of
                    precaution for the safety of Spanish priests, might consider it prudent to urge
                    her nationals engaged in religious work in Mexico to retire from that country
                    for the present. The above is communicated merely for your information and for
                    such action as you may desire to take in connection therewith.</p>
            </div>
